":"Ayrshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Berkeley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from one or more of the numerous places so named, such as Berkeley in Gloucestershire, named in Old English with <i>be(o)rc</i> ‘birch’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’. Compare Scottish   Barclay  .","Jewish (American): adoption of the English surname (see 1 above) in place of   Berkowitz  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Barclay","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name of English origin, from any of several places so called, such as Berkley in Somerset or Berkeley in Gloucestershire, both named in Old English with <i>be(o)rc</i> ‘birch’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’.","History: The surname was brought to Scotland from southwestern England in the 12th century; Walter de Berchelai or Berkelai was Chamberlain of Scotland in 1165. It was long assumed that they were from the family that held Berkeley Castle in Gloucestershire, but the historian G. W. S. Barrow (1973, <i>The Kingdom of the Scots</i>) adduced evidence that they are more probably from Berkley in Somerset."]},{"name":"Berkley","meanings":["English: variant of   Berkeley  . Compare Scottish   Barclay  .","Jewish (Ashkenazic): assimilated form of   Berkowitz  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir John de Berkeley II  of Kilbirnie was born in 1267, in Kilbirnie, Ayrshire, Scotland, his father, Sir Walter de Berkeley - First Laird of Kilbirnie, was 40 and his mother, Margaret de Craufurd, was 30. He had at least 1 son."},"et":{"1267–":"1267–Surnud","1267–Male":"1267–Surnud","1305–Male":"1305–Surnud","1227–1285":"1227–1285","1237–Femal